# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: asa-gray
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:asa-gray/a-history-of-british-birds] The book was effectively the first "field guide" for non-specialists.
[src:asa-gray/a-history-of-british-birds] Bewick provides an accurate illustration of each species, from life if possible, or from skins.
[src:asa-gray/a-history-of-british-birds] The common and scientific name(s) are listed, citing the naming authorities.
[src:asa-gray/a-history-of-british-birds] The bird is described, with its distribution and behaviour, often with extensive quotations from printed sources or correspondents.
[src:asa-gray/a-history-of-british-birds] Those who provided skins or information are acknowledged.
[src:asa-gray/a-history-of-british-birds] The species are grouped into families such as "Of the Falcon", using the limited and conflicting scientific sources of the time.
[src:asa-gray/a-history-of-british-birds] The families of land birds are further grouped into birds of prey, omnivorous birds, insectivorous birds, and granivorous birds, while the families of water birds are simply listed, with related families side by side.
[src:asa-gray/a-history-of-british-birds] Each species entry begins on a new page; any spaces at the ends of entries are filled with tail-pieces, small, often humorous woodcuts of country life.
[src:asa-gray/a-history-of-british-birds] *British Birds* remains in print, and has attracted the attention of authors such as Jenny Uglow.
[src:asa-gray/a-history-of-british-birds] Critics note Bewick's skill as a naturalist as well as an engraver.
[src:asa-gray/a-history-of-british-birds] The arrangement of the species was by alphabetical order in Gessner's *Historia animalium*, and by arbitrary criteria in most other early works.
[src:asa-gray/a-history-of-british-birds] The first modern ornithology, intended to describe all the then-known birds worldwide, was produced by Ray and Willughby and published in Latin as *Ornithologiae Libri Tres* (*Three Books of Ornithology*) in 1676, and in English, as *The Ornithology of Francis Willughby of Middleton*, in 1678.
[src:asa-gray/a-history-of-british-birds] Its innovative features were an effective classification system based on anatomical features, including the bird's beak, feet and overall size, and a dichotomous key, which helped readers to identify birds by guiding them to the page describing that group.
[src:asa-gray/a-history-of-british-birds] The authors also placed an asterisk against species of which they had no first-hand knowledge, and were therefore unable to verify.
[src:asa-gray/a-history-of-british-birds] The commercial success of the *Ornithology* is unknown, but it was historically significant, influencing writers including René Réaumur, Mathurin Jacques Brisson, Georges Cuvier and Carl Linnaeus in compiling their own works.
[src:asa-gray/a-history-of-british-birds] George Edwards was a leading British naturalist and illustrator in the 17th century.
[src:asa-gray/a-history-of-british-birds] He was the librarian to the Royal College of Physicians with access to their collection of 8,000 books, and he used these, together with stuffed and live animals, to produce illustrated publications.
[src:asa-gray/a-history-of-british-birds] His four-volume *A Natural History of Uncommon Birds* (1743–1751) and its three supplements covered more than 600 natural history topics, and his publications enabled Linnaeus to name 350 bird species, including many type specimens.
[src:asa-gray/a-history-of-british-birds] When he was researching published sources for his bird project, Bewick relied particularly on Edwards' book and the multi-volume *Histoire Naturelle* of the French naturalist Georges-Louis Leclerc, Comte de Buffon.
[src:asa-gray/a-history-of-british-birds] Thomas Bewick was born at Cherryburn, a house in the parish of Mickley, Northumberland, and he was apprenticed at the age of 14 to Ralph Beilby, an engraver in Newcastle upon Tyne, and learnt how to engrave on wood and metal.
[src:asa-gray/a-history-of-british-birds] The business prospered, becoming Newcastle's leading engraving service with an enviable reputation for high-quality work and good service.
[src:asa-gray/a-history-of-british-birds] Now partners, Bielby and Bewick published their *History of Quadrupeds* in 1790, and its success encouraged them to consider producing a new book on British birds.
[src:asa-gray/a-history-of-british-birds] In preparation for this major work, Bewick spent several years engraving the necessary wood blocks.
[src:asa-gray/a-history-of-british-birds] Bewick became well known for his engravings, including the woodcuts for Oliver Goldsmith's *Traveller* and *The Deserted Village*, for Thomas Parnell's *Hermit*, and for William Somervile's *Chase*.
[src:asa-gray/a-history-of-british-birds] Perhaps the best known of his prints is *The Chillingham Bull*, executed on an exceptionally large woodblock for Marmaduke Tunstall, a Yorkshire landowner.
[src:asa-gray/a-history-of-british-birds] Bewick also produced and illustrated several editions of Aesop's Fables throughout his creative life.
[src:asa-gray/a-history-of-british-birds] His success meant that Bewick had at least 30 pupils who worked for him and Beilby as apprentices, the first of whom was his younger brother John.
[src:asa-gray/a-history-of-british-birds] Bewick died at his home on 8 November 1828.
[src:asa-gray/a-history-of-british-birds] He was buried in Ovingham churchyard, beside his late wife Isabella, who had died two years earlier on 1 February 1826, and not far from his parents and his brother John.
[src:asa-gray/a-history-of-british-birds] The preface to *A History of British Birds* states that "while one of the editors [Bewick] of this work was engaged in preparing the cuts, which are faithfully drawn from Nature, and engraved upon wood, the compilation of the descriptions ..
[src:asa-gray/a-history-of-british-birds] What the preface does not say is the reason for this statement about the "editors", which was an angry stand-off between Bewick and Beilby.
[src:asa-gray/a-history-of-british-birds] Beilby's original intention was to have an introduction which merely thanked Bewick for his "assistance", and a title-page naming Beilby as the sole author.
[src:asa-gray/a-history-of-british-birds] Bewick's friend (and his wife's godfather) Thomas Hornby heard of this, and informed Bewick.
[src:asa-gray/a-history-of-british-birds] An informal trade panel met to judge the matter, and the preface as printed was the result; Beilby's name did not appear on the title-page.
[src:asa-gray/a-history-of-british-birds] Each species of bird is presented in a few pages (generally between two and four; occasionally, as with the mallard or "Common Wild Duck", a few more).
[src:asa-gray/a-history-of-british-birds] The first item is a woodcut print of the bird, always either perched or standing on the ground, even in the case of water birds – such as the smew – that (as winter visitors) do not nest in Britain, and consequently are rarely seen away from water there.
[src:asa-gray/a-history-of-british-birds] Bewick then presents the name, with variations, and the Latin and French equivalents.
[src:asa-gray/a-history-of-british-birds] For example, "The Musk Duck" is also named on the line below as "Cairo, Guinea, or Indian Duck", and the next line "(*Anas moschata*, Linn.—*Le Canard Musque*, Buff.)" provides the scholarly references to the giving of the Latin binomial by Linnaeus (Linn) and a French description by Buffon (Buff).
[src:asa-gray/a-history-of-british-birds] The text begins by stating the size of the bird.
[src:asa-gray/a-history-of-british-birds] Bewick then describes the bird, typically in one paragraph, naming any notable features such as the colour of the eyes ("irides"), the bill, the legs, and plumage on each part of the body.
[src:asa-gray/a-history-of-british-birds] Next, the origin and distribution of the species are discussed, with notes or quotations from authorities such as John Ray, Gilbert White and Buffon.
[src:asa-gray/a-history-of-british-birds] Bewick then mentions any other facts of interest about the bird; in the case of the musk duck, this concerns its "musky smell, which arises from the liquor secreted in the glands on the rump".
[src:asa-gray/a-history-of-british-birds] If the bird hybridizes with other species, this is described, along with whether the hybrids are fertile ("productive").
[src:asa-gray/a-history-of-british-birds] Finally, Bewick acknowledges anyone who had helped him.
[src:asa-gray/a-history-of-british-birds] The musk duck is stated to have been drawn from a "living specimen" which was however "excepting the head, entirely white", unlike the "general appearance" shown in the woodcut; the bird "was lent to this work by William Losh, Esq., of Point Pleasant, near Newcastle".
[src:asa-gray/a-history-of-british-birds] Losh, one of Bewick's many collaborators, was a wealthy partner in Losh, Wilson and Bell, manufacturers of chemicals and iron.
[src:asa-gray/a-history-of-british-birds] Many of the birds, especially the rarer species, were necessarily illustrated from skins rather than from life.
[src:asa-gray/a-history-of-british-birds] For example, for the Sabine's snipe, "The author was favoured by N.
[src:asa-gray/a-history-of-british-birds] The grouping of species gave Bewick difficulty, as the scientific sources of the time did not agree on how to arrange the species in families, or on a sequence or grouping of those families.
[src:asa-gray/a-history-of-british-birds] Bewick, for example, uses family groups like "Of the Falcon", in which he includes buzzards and sparrowhawks as well as what are now called falcons.
[src:asa-gray/a-history-of-british-birds] Each account is closed with a miniature woodcut known from its position in the text as a tail-piece.
[src:asa-gray/a-history-of-british-birds] These small artworks depict aspects of country life, often with humorous subjects, but all with Bewick's eye for detail, style, and precision.
[src:asa-gray/a-history-of-british-birds] Some add to the illustration of the bird in question, as for example the heron, where the tail-piece shows one heron catching an eel, and another flying away.
[src:asa-gray/a-history-of-british-birds] The tail-piece for Sabine's snipe, a gamebird, shows a hunter firing, and a small bird falling to the ground.
[src:asa-gray/a-history-of-british-birds] There is no exclusion of human life from the images: one tail-piece depicts a works complete with smoking chimney beside a river.
[src:asa-gray/a-history-of-british-birds] The first volume "containing the History and Description of Land Birds" begins with a preface, an introduction, and a list of technical terms illustrated with Bewick's woodcuts.
[src:asa-gray/a-history-of-british-birds] The birds are divided into granivorous (grain eating) and carnivorous groups, which are explained in some detail.
[src:asa-gray/a-history-of-british-birds] The speed, senses, flight, migration, pairing behaviour and feeding of birds are then discussed, with observations from Spallanzani and Gilbert White, whose *Natural History and Antiquities of Selborne* was published in 1789.
[src:asa-gray/a-history-of-british-birds] The second volume "containing the History and Description of Water Birds" begins with its own preface, and its own introduction.
[src:asa-gray/a-history-of-british-birds] Bewick discusses the question of where many seabirds go to breed, revisits the subject of migration, and concludes with reflections on "an all-wise Providence" as shown in Nature.
[src:asa-gray/a-history-of-british-birds] The 'foreign birds' are not grouped but just listed directly as species, from Bearded Vulture to Mino.
[src:asa-gray/a-history-of-british-birds] Fifteen birds are included, with no description, and despite their placement in the table of contents, they appear at the front of the volume as an 'Appendix'.
[src:asa-gray/a-history-of-british-birds] Bewick's *Birds* was an immediate best-seller.
[src:asa-gray/a-history-of-british-birds] When *Land Birds* appeared, the whole print sold out by the middle of 1798; 1000 copies of the demy size (8+3⁄4 in × 5+5⁄8 in, 220 mm × 140 mm), 850 of the royal octavo (10 in × 6+1⁄4 in, 250 mm × 160 mm), and 24 of the grand imperial (22 in × 30 in, 560 mm × 760 mm).
[src:asa-gray/a-history-of-british-birds] The 1829 *Magazine of Natural History* commented that "Montagu's *Ornithological Dictionary* and Bewick's *Birds* .. have rendered [the] department of natural history popular throughout the land".
[src:asa-gray/a-history-of-british-birds] The Tate Gallery writes that Bewick's " best illustrations ... are in his natural history books.
[src:asa-gray/a-history-of-british-birds] Dissenting from the general tone of praise for Bewick, Jacob Kainen cites claims that "many of the best tailpieces in the *History of British birds* were drawn by Robert Johnson", and that "the greater number of those contained in the second volume were engraved by Clennell.
[src:asa-gray/a-history-of-british-birds] To Bewick, nature was the source of joy, challenge and perpetual consolation.
[src:asa-gray/a-history-of-british-birds] Hilary Spurling, reviewing Uglow's biography of Bewick in *The Observer*, writes that when *Birds* appeared, people all over Britain "became his pupils".
[src:asa-gray/a-history-of-british-birds] Spurling cites Charles Kingsley's story of his father's hunting friends from the New Forest mocking him for buying "a book 'about dicky-birds", until, astonished, they saw the book and discovered "things they had known all their lives and never even noticed".
[src:asa-gray/a-history-of-british-birds] The *History* is repeatedly mentioned in Charlotte Brontë's 1847 novel *Jane Eyre*.
[src:asa-gray/a-history-of-british-birds] John Reed throws the *History of British Birds* at Jane when she is ten; Jane uses the book as a place to which to escape, away from the painful Reed household; and Jane also bases her artwork on Bewick's illustrations.
[src:asa-gray/a-history-of-british-birds] Jane and Mr Rochester use bird names for each other, including linnet, dove, skylark, eagle, and falcon.
[src:asa-gray/a-history-of-british-birds] Peter Hall's 1974 film *Akenfield* (from the 1969 book by Ronald Blythe) contains a scene where the grandfather as a young man is reaping a cornfield.
[src:asa-gray/a-history-of-british-birds] He weeps when he accidentally crushes a bird's egg, an image derived from Bewick's tail-piece woodcut for the partridge.
[src:asa-gray/a-history-of-british-birds] The woodcut shows a reaper with a scythe, a dead bird and its nest of a dozen eggs on the ground under the scythe, which has just lifted.
[src:asa-gray/a-history-of-british-birds] George Ewart Evans used the image on the title-page of his 1956 book about Blaxhall (near Charsfield, on which 'Akenfield' is probably partly based).
[src:asa-gray/a-history-of-british-birds] Bewick's reputation as a wood engraver was at its height in the nineteenth century, with the critic John Ruskin writing that the way Bewick had engraved the feathers of his birds was "the most masterly thing ever done in woodcutting".
[src:asa-gray/a-history-of-british-birds] The advent of mechanical printing techniques from the 1860s led to something of a decline in his importance, but his fame, already nationwide across Britain for his *Birds*, grew during the nineteenth century.
[src:asa-gray/a-history-of-british-birds] In 1830, William Yarrell named Bewick's swan in his honour, and Bewick's son Robert engraved the bird for later editions of *British Birds*.
[src:asa-gray/a-history-of-british-birds] Bewick had met the American naturalist and bird painter John James Audubon in 1827, and had given him a copy of his *Quadrupeds* for his children.
[src:asa-gray/a-history-of-british-birds] The American returned the compliment by naming a newly-discovered US bird species as Bewick's wren in honour of his friend.
[src:asa-gray/a-history-of-british-birds] The way in which Bewick had organised the text and illustrations in his *Birds* takes the form of, and sets a precedent for, modern field guides.
[src:asa-gray/a-history-of-british-birds] Indeed, the French naturalist François Holandre (1753–1830) assembled a field guide using Bewick's woodcuts as early as 1800.
[src:asa-gray/a-history-of-british-birds] A selection of tail-pieces from the book, where they have no captions.
[src:asa-gray/a-history-of-british-birds] Volume 1 first appeared in 1797, and was reprinted several times in 1797, then again in 1798 and 1800.
[src:asa-gray/a-history-of-british-birds] Volume 2 first appeared in 1804 (price 11.
[src:asa-gray/a-history-of-british-birds] The first imprint was "Newcastle : Printed by Sol.
[src:asa-gray/a-history-of-british-birds] Hodgson, for Beilby & Bewick; London: Sold by them, and G.C. and J.
[src:asa-gray/a-history-of-british-birds] In 1821 a new edition appeared with supplements to both volumes and additional figures, with the imprint "Printed by Edward Walker, Pilgrim-Street, for T.
[src:asa-gray/a-history-of-british-birds] Charnley, Newcastle; and Longman and co., London, 1821." The book was reprinted in many subsequent versions with a 6th edition in 1826, another in 1832, an 8th edition in 1847, and a royal octavo 'Memorial Edition' in 1885.
[src:asa-gray/a-hunter-dupree] Dupree, and his wife, Sarah Hunter, he attended Oberlin College, where he earned his Bachelor of Arts degree (summa cum laude) in 1942.
[src:asa-gray/a-hunter-dupree] Upon completion of his undergraduate work, he served the United States Navy from 1942 to 1946, and became a Lieutenant in the U.S.
[src:asa-gray/a-hunter-dupree] At the end of World War II, Dupree married Marguerite Louise (Betty) Arnold (c.
[src:asa-gray/a-hunter-dupree] 1918-May 27, 2014) of Seattle on July 18, 1946, having two children including the historian Marguerite Dupree and the harpsichord maker Anderson H.
[src:asa-gray/a-hunter-dupree] Hunter Dupree entered Harvard University, where he completed his master's degree in 1947, and his Ph.D. in 1952, having written his doctoral dissertation on Asa Gray, titled "Asa Gray: The Development of a Statesman of Science, 1810–1848".
[src:asa-gray/a-hunter-dupree] Marguerite earned a Ph.D. in history from Harvard and also taught at universities.
[src:asa-gray/a-hunter-dupree] In 1950, Dupree took up his first academic position as assistant professor of history at Texas Technological College (now Texas Tech University) in Lubbock, Texas, where he remained until 1952, when he was appointed a research fellow at the Gray Herbarium at Harvard University.
[src:asa-gray/a-hunter-dupree] He served two appointments there in 1952–54 and 1955–56.
[src:asa-gray/a-hunter-dupree] In addition, he served as project director on grants at the National Science Foundation, 1953–55.
[src:asa-gray/a-hunter-dupree] In 1956, the University of California, Berkeley appointed Dupree as visiting assistant professor of history, then promoted to associate professor in 1958, and professor of history in 1961.
[src:asa-gray/a-hunter-dupree] He served additionally as assistant to the chancellor in 1960–62, and director of the Bancroft Library in 1965–66.
[src:asa-gray/a-hunter-dupree] In addition, Dupree was a consultant to the committee on science and public policy at the National Academy of Sciences in 1963–64.
[src:asa-gray/a-hunter-dupree] Despite being a competent academic, Dupree's tenure in the Bancroft Library directorship was brief and stormy.
[src:asa-gray/a-hunter-dupree] He was appointed to the directorship in June 1965 but clashed repeatedly with the staff over library internal policy, which sparked a near-revolution among its employees.
[src:asa-gray/a-hunter-dupree] Part of the disagreement involved Dupree's emphasis on modernizing traditional library practices and the way collections, particularly manuscripts, were handled in the collections.
[src:asa-gray/a-hunter-dupree] He also required an accounting for long-term projects on which the library devoted resources but could show few actual results.
[src:asa-gray/a-hunter-dupree] In January 1966 The UC-Berkeley president returned him to the history faculty that same June.
[src:asa-gray/a-hunter-dupree] In 1968, Brown University appointed Dupree George L.
[src:asa-gray/a-hunter-dupree] Littlefield Professor of History, a position he held until his retirement in 1981.
[src:asa-gray/a-hunter-dupree] While in this post, he served as a consultant to the Panel on Science and Technology and Astronautics, U.S.
[src:asa-gray/a-hunter-dupree] House of Representatives, 1969–73; trustee of the American Textile History Museum, a member of the NASA Historical Advisory Committee, and the Atomic Energy Commission's Historical Advisory Committee.
